Chapter 5: Reduction to Known Architectures

5.1 Natural Gradient Descent

If we set \lambda = 0, the intentional flow reduces to

\dot{\theta} = -F(\theta)^{-1} \nabla \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}}.

This is exactly natural gradient descent (Amari, 1998). By Proposition 2.1, if \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}} is convex, then \mathcal{L}_0 is geodesically convex, and Theorem 4.2 guarantees exponential convergence.

5.2 Transformers as Fisher-Contracting Maps

Proposition 5.1 (Attention is Fisher-contracting). Let M be a statistical manifold of token embeddings. An attention head with softmax activation defines a map \operatorname{Attn}: M^n \to M^n that is a morphism in Stat with Lipschitz constant L \le 1.

Proof. Each output coordinate is a convex combination of input distributions via a stochastic matrix (the attention weights). By Cencov's theorem, Markov kernels are Fisher contractions. The product metric on M^n extends this property coordinatewise. ∎

5.3 Attention Residuals as Intentional Flows

Proposition 5.2. Let the layers of a deep network be objects M_1, \ldots, M_L in Stat. Define the residual stream as the product manifold R = M_1 \times \cdots \times M_L. Then:

1. Standard residual connections correspond to a fixed morphism \rho_{\text{std}}: R \to R with constant weights 1/L.
2. Full Attention Residuals correspond to a learned morphism \rho_{\text{attn}}: R \to R with weights \alpha_l(\theta) computed via depth-wise attention .
3. Block Attention Residuals correspond to a morphism that factors through a reduced product of N block representations, with communication cost reduced from O(Ld) to O(Nd) .

