Corollary 5.3 (Stability of Softmax layers). Since \rho > 0 for the simplex, composition through softmax layers is inherently stable—the curvature term in Theorem 4.3 becomes -\frac{\rho}{2}d^2, aiding convergence. This provides a mathematical basis for the empirical stability of attention-based architectures.

5.5 Kimi Delta Attention and DPLR Conditioning

The Kimi Linear architecture  uses a hybrid of Kimi Delta Attention (KDA) and Multi-Head Latent Attention (MLA). KDA employs a Diagonal-Plus-Low-Rank (DPLR) transition:

S_t = \Lambda_t S_{t-1} + U_t V_t^\top,\quad \Lambda_t = \text{Diag}(\alpha_t).

Proposition 5.4 (Metric conditioning of KDA). Under the assumptions that U_t, V_t are Fisher-contracting (as linear maps), the eigenvalues of the Fisher information matrix g_t satisfy

\lambda_{\min}(g_t) \ge \lambda_{\min}(g_0) \prod_{s=1}^t \min(1, \alpha_s^2),\quad \lambda_{\max}(g_t) \le \lambda_{\max}(g_0) \prod_{s=1}^t \max(1, \alpha_s^2).

Proof. The Fisher information of the state S_t evolves according to the Jacobian of the update. Since the update is linear in S_{t-1} plus a low-rank term, the Jacobian is \Lambda_t plus a low-rank matrix. By the Fisher-contracting property, the low-rank term does not increase the operator norm beyond the diagonal scaling. Hence the eigenvalues are bounded multiplicatively by the diagonal entries \alpha_t. ∎

This result ensures that even after millions of steps, the metric remains well-conditioned, enabling stable training over extremely long contexts—as demonstrated by the 1M context length of Kimi models .

