Chapter 7: Stochastic Intentional Flows and Future Directions

7.1 Stochastic Extension

We extend the deterministic intentional flow to a Langevin SDE on (M, g):

d\theta_t = -\text{grad}_g \mathcal{L}_\lambda(\theta_t) dt + \sqrt{2\beta^{-1}} dW_t

where dW_t is the Brownian motion on M (generated by the Laplace-Beltrami operator). The invariant measure is the Gibbs distribution \pi(\theta) \propto e^{-\beta \mathcal{L}_\lambda(\theta)}.

Theorem 7.1 (Convergence to Gibbs measure). Assume \operatorname{Ric}_g \ge \rho g and \mathcal{L}_\lambda is \mu-strongly convex. Then the transition kernel P_t of the Langevin diffusion satisfies the log-Sobolev inequality with constant \alpha \ge \mu + \rho, and consequently

\chi^2(P_t f \parallel \pi) \le e^{-2\alpha t} \chi^2(f \parallel \pi)

for any function f with \int f d\pi = 0. In particular, the law of \theta_t converges exponentially to \pi in relative entropy.

Proof. The Bakry-Émery criterion states that if \operatorname{Ric} + \nabla^2 \mathcal{L}_\lambda \ge \alpha g, then the generator satisfies a curvature-dimension condition CD(\alpha, \infty), which implies a log-Sobolev inequality with constant \alpha. Here \nabla^2 \mathcal{L}_\lambda \ge \mu g and \operatorname{Ric} \ge \rho g, so \operatorname{Ric} + \nabla^2 \mathcal{L}_\lambda \ge (\mu + \rho) g. Thus \alpha = \mu + \rho. The exponential convergence in \chi^2 follows from standard theory . ∎

This provides the first formal guarantee that stochastic training (SGD) in AttnRes architectures still reaches the geometric optimum, with a rate governed by the curvature and convexity.

7.2 Implications for Safe AI

The theorems in this thesis provide the first mathematically rigorous guarantees for stability in goal-directed learning systems:

· Convergence guarantee (Theorem 4.2): Any system minimizing a strongly geodesically convex regularized loss will converge exponentially to a unique fixed point.
· Compositional stability (Theorem 4.3): Stable components can be combined safely under curvature conditions, even when connecting maps expand distances.
· Architectural optimality (Theorem 4.5): Attention Residuals are provably superior to standard residuals because they enable metric alignment with task geometry, explaining their 1.25× compute advantage .
· Stochastic robustness (Theorem 7.1): Even with noise, the system converges exponentially to the Gibbs measure, ensuring that random fluctuations do not destabilize learning.

These results offer a foundation for verifiable AI: before deploying a system, one could in principle check that its loss is geodesically convex (or at least satisfies PL) and that its modules satisfy curvature-Lipschitz conditions, thereby guaranteeing stability.

7.3 Limitations

· Parametric assumption: The framework assumes exponential families; extending to non-parametric settings requires functional information geometry.
· Deterministic dynamics in core theorems: The stochastic extension is given but not fully integrated with the categorical framework; this is left for future work.
· Convexity is strong: Many real losses are non-convex; we rely on approximate stability results.

